emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()) — correct way to shift blocking I/O off Vert.x IO thread in a reactive SPI

## Context

A reactive SPI method returns `Uni<T>` and needs to make a blocking call (e.g. HTTP to an embedding service, JDBC, file I/O). The SPI is called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler (Vert.x event bus) which runs on the Vert.x IO thread unless `blocking = true` is set.

## Technique

Use `.emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())` on the `Uni` **before** the blocking operation. This shifts the execution to the Mutiny default worker pool:

```java
@Override
public Uni<AgentAssignment> select(AgentRoutingContext context, List<AgentCandidate> candidates) {
    // Classify (in-memory, fast — can stay on caller thread)
    List<ClassifiedCandidate> classified = classifier.classify(candidates, ...);

return Uni.createFrom()
        .voidItem()
        .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())  // shift here, before blocking work
        .map(ignored -> {
            // Everything from here runs on the worker pool
            float[] queryVector = embeddingProvider.embed(queryText);  // blocking HTTP call
            // ... build scored candidates ...
            return TrustCandidateClassifier.decide(classified, scored, capability);
        });
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

Three common but wrong alternatives:

**1. `Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blockingOperation())`**
Executes the supplier on the thread that subscribes (the IO thread). Still blocks if called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler.

**2. `@Blocking` on the handler method**
Moves the *entire* handler to a worker thread, including all in-memory work before the SPI call. Wasteful and scatters the threading decision into the caller rather than the SPI implementation.

**3. `Uni.createFrom().emitter(em -> { em.complete(blocking()); })`**
Also executes on the subscribing thread unless `.emitOn()` is chained.

The correct model: the `Uni` pipeline is lazy. `.emitOn(workerPool)` inserts a thread-handoff at that point in the pipeline — everything downstream of it executes on the worker pool when the `Uni` is subscribed. Place it immediately before the first blocking call, after any fast in-memory preparation.

## Constraints

Requires `io.smallrye.mutiny:mutiny` and `io.smallrye.mutiny.infrastructure.Infrastructure` on the classpath (shipped with Quarkus). `Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()` is the standard Mutiny executor for blocking work — do not pass a custom executor unless you need isolation.

**See also:** [GE-20260529-b994c2](GE-20260529-b994c2.md) — Uni.createFrom().item(supplier) with emitOn(): supplier still runs on subscription thread (use runSubscriptionOn instead)

Panache.withTransaction() requires a duplicated Vert.x context — executeBlocking() root context still fails VertxContextSafetyToggle

### Symptom

Error changes from "No current Vertx context found" to "Can't get the context safety flag: the current context is not a duplicated context" — wrapping the call in `vertx.executeBlocking()` seemed to fix the first error but the operation still fails.

### Context

Triggered when calling `Panache.withTransaction()` (or `withSession()`) from a `@BeforeEach` test method or other code that isn't on a proper Quarkus-managed request thread. Adding `vertx.executeBlocking()` provides *a* Vert.x context but not the right kind.

### Root cause

`SessionOperations.vertxContext()` in Quarkus Hibernate Reactive checks two things:
1. A Vert.x context exists (`Vertx.currentContext()`)
2. `VertxContextSafetyToggle.checkIsSafe()` — the context must be a *duplicated* context (`context.duplicate()`)

Worker threads from `vertx.executeBlocking()` run in a root context. Root contexts fail the safety check even though they are valid Vert.x contexts.

### Fix

**Option 1 — `@Blocking` on endpoint/method (production code):**
```java
@GET
@Path("/{id}/lineage")
@Blocking
public Response getLineage(@PathParam("id") String id) {
    return Response.ok(service.findAll().await().indefinitely()).build();
}
```
Quarkus creates a properly duplicated context for `@Blocking` method invocations.

**Option 2 — `@RunOnVertxContext` for test lifecycle methods:**
```java
@BeforeEach
@RunOnVertxContext
Uni<Void> setup() {
    return service.create("test-channel", ...).replaceWithVoid();
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Two different error messages for two related but distinct constraints, encountered sequentially. A developer who added `executeBlocking()` to fix the first "No Vert.x context" error reasonably believes they are on the right track — the error did change. The duplicated-context requirement is not documented in `Panache.withTransaction()` JavaDoc and only appears via the internal safety toggle.

**See also:** [GE-20260529-78ecb9](GE-20260529-78ecb9.md) — @QuarkusTest methods calling Panache.withTransaction() on JUnit thread fail with 'No current Vertx context'

**See also:** [GE-20260616-312ba1](GE-20260616-312ba1.md) — @WithSession requires a safe Vert.x sub-context | [GE-20260616-99484f](GE-20260616-99484f.md) — Uni.combine() technique for concurrent blocking + reactive

PanacheRepository<PlainEntity, UUID> listAll() throws implementationInjectionMissing at runtime when entity is plain @Entity

## Symptom

At runtime, calling `repo.listAll()` (or other Panache repository methods) throws:

```
java.lang.IllegalStateException: This method is normally automatically overridden in subclasses:
did you forget to annotate your entity with @Entity?
    at io.quarkus.hibernate.orm.panache.common.runtime.AbstractJpaOperations.implementationInjectionMissing
    at io.quarkus.hibernate.orm.panache.PanacheRepositoryBase.listAll
```

The entity does have `@Entity`. The error message is completely misleading.

## Context

Occurs when a repository class implements `PanacheRepository<Entity, Id>` (or `PanacheRepositoryBase<Entity, Id>`) but the entity is a plain JPA `@Entity` POJO that does **not** extend `PanacheEntityBase` or `PanacheEntity`.

## Root Cause

Quarkus Panache's bytecode enhancement for repository methods (the automatic method override mentioned in the error) is only applied to repositories whose entity type went through Panache's own build-time processor. That processor only recognises entities that extend `PanacheEntityBase`. A plain `@Entity` is never processed by Panache's build step, so the repository methods are never enhanced — the stubs remain and throw at runtime.

## Fix

Do **not** use `PanacheRepository<PlainEntity, Id>` when the entity is a plain JPA POJO. Instead, inject `EntityManager` directly and use JPQL:

```java
@ApplicationScoped
@Alternative
public class JpaLedgerEntryRepository implements LedgerEntryRepository {

@Inject
    EntityManager em;

@Override
    public List<LedgerEntry> findBySubjectId(UUID subjectId) {
        return em.createQuery(
            "SELECT e FROM LedgerEntry e WHERE e.subjectId = :id ORDER BY e.sequenceNumber ASC",
            LedgerEntry.class)
            .setParameter("id", subjectId)
            .getResultList();
    }
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

The Quarkus docs describe `PanacheRepository<Entity, Id>` as a "repository pattern" suitable for any JPA entity — distinct from the active-record pattern that requires `PanacheEntityBase`. The docs don't mention that the entity must still be processed by Panache's build step. The error message says "did you forget to annotate with @Entity" which actively misleads — the entity has `@Entity` and that's not the problem.

**See also:** GE-20260420-b9259e (LedgerAttestation plain @Entity — Panache statics cause compile error)

RESTEasy Reactive endpoints that call .await() on the IO thread throw BlockingOperationNotAllowedException — add @Blocking

## RESTEasy Reactive endpoints that call .await() on the IO thread throw BlockingOperationNotAllowedException — add @Blocking

### Symptom

A RESTEasy Reactive endpoint that unwraps a reactive result with `.await().atMost(TIMEOUT)` works fine in tests (low concurrency, small H2 responses) but throws `BlockingOperationNotAllowedException` in production under load. The exception is thrown inside the Vert.x IO thread guard.

### Context

This surfaces when switching from a blocking API (returning `List<T>` directly) to a reactive API (returning `Uni<List<T>>`), and adapting by calling `.await()`:

```java
// quarkus-rest-jackson (RESTEasy Reactive) — IO thread by default
@GET
@Path("/channels")
public List<ChannelDetail> channels() {
    return reactiveService.listChannels().await().atMost(Duration.ofSeconds(10));  // ← blocks IO thread
}
```

The endpoint returns `List<T>` (not `Uni<T>` or `Multi<T>`), so RESTEasy Reactive dispatches it on the Vert.x IO thread. The `.await()` call then blocks that IO thread, which Vert.x prohibits.

### Root cause

RESTEasy Reactive runs endpoint methods on the Vert.x IO event loop by default. Blocking the event loop — even for a short duration — starves all other I/O operations. Vert.x detects this and throws `BlockingOperationNotAllowedException`.

The original blocking API (e.g. `QhorusMcpTools.listChannels()` returning `List<T>`) had the same structural problem but may not have surfaced it depending on the CDI dispatch context. Switching to a reactive API and calling `.await()` makes the blocking explicit and the guard fires.

### Fix

**Short-term:** Annotate blocking endpoints with `@Blocking` so RESTEasy Reactive dispatches them to a worker thread:

```java
@GET
@Path("/channels")
@Blocking   // io.smallrye.common.annotation.Blocking
public List<ChannelDetail> channels() {
    return reactiveService.listChannels().await().atMost(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
}
```

**Proper fix:** Return `Uni<T>` directly and let RESTEasy Reactive subscribe on the IO thread without blocking:

```java
@GET
@Path("/channels")
public Uni<List<ChannelDetail>> channels() {
    return reactiveService.listChannels();
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

- Classic `quarkus-resteasy` dispatches all endpoints to worker threads — `.await()` works there without annotation.
- The endpoint compiles, starts, and passes unit/integration tests because test HTTP clients are synchronous and concurrency is low.
- The `BlockingOperationNotAllowedException` only surfaces under real Vert.x IO thread dispatch — which requires `quarkus-rest` or `quarkus-resteasy-reactive` and actual concurrent load.
- The error message points to the `.await()` call site, but the root cause is the missing `@Blocking` or return-type change on the endpoint.

**See also:** [GE-20260526-399a43](GE-20260526-399a43.md) — quarkus-rest + JDBC Panache requires @Blocking — tests pass without it, production degrades silently

**See also:** [GE-20260617-36c6b5](GE-20260617-36c6b5.md) — @Blocking required on quarkus-rest JAX-RS handlers with polling loops | [GE-20260617-c2ceb3](GE-20260617-c2ceb3.md) — @Transactional on RESTEasy Reactive void SSE method

@Startup @ApplicationScoped prevents blocking @PostConstruct from running on Vert.x IO thread

# @Startup @ApplicationScoped prevents blocking @PostConstruct from running on Vert.x IO thread

## The technique

Add `@Startup` to any `@ApplicationScoped` bean whose `@PostConstruct` makes a blocking call:

```java
@Startup           // forces eager init on main thread during boot
@ApplicationScoped
public class MyClient {

@PostConstruct
    void validate() {
        // blocking: process probe, network check, file I/O, etc.
        new ProcessBuilder("claude", "--version").start().waitFor(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
    }
}
```

Without `@Startup`, Quarkus ARC initializes `@ApplicationScoped` beans **lazily** — on first injection. If the first injection happens from a reactive handler (inside a Vert.x event-loop callback, a REST endpoint, a CDI observer), the `@PostConstruct` runs on the Vert.x IO thread. Any blocking call there violates the non-blocking contract and either deadlocks under load or triggers a `BlockingOperationNotAllowedException`.

`@Startup` forces initialization during application boot on the main thread, before any reactive handlers are active.

## Why this is non-obvious

`@Startup` is documented as "run initialization at startup" but the docs frame it in terms of *when* (boot vs. first use), not *which thread*. The connection to IO-thread safety is not mentioned. Developers who know about `@Startup` typically use it for "I want this to run at boot time" — not as a reactive-safety mechanism.

The failure mode is intermittent: `@PostConstruct` is safe when the first injection happens from a non-reactive context (tests, CLI, HTTP request on a worker thread). It only fails when the first injection happens under reactive load — making it a production-only bug in many setups.

## Codebase pattern

Same pattern used by `PathParserConfigurator` and `MongoPreferenceIndexes` in casehub-platform. Canonical for any bean that initialises eagerly and blocks during `@PostConstruct`.

## Why non-obvious

The standard mental model for `@ApplicationScoped` is "singleton, available everywhere, initialized once." The lazy-init detail — and its thread-safety implications in a reactive runtime — is not in the CDI spec, only in Quarkus ARC internals. A developer migrating from Spring (`@Bean` methods always run on the startup thread) would have no reason to anticipate the problem.

**See also:** [GE-20260522-daca26](GE-20260522-daca26.md) — Mutiny MultiEmitter.emit() from Vert.x I/O thread silently drops SSE frames | [GE-20260505-da346d](GE-20260505-da346d.md) — @ApplicationScoped CDI beans are always-active in Quarkus

**See also:** [GE-20260605-e42cc5](GE-20260605-e42cc5.md) — @Blocking on plain @ApplicationScoped method causes Quarkus test classloader failure

**See also:** [GE-20260607-cedf69](GE-20260607-cedf69.md) — @Startup @ApplicationScoped does not auto-invoke arbitrary methods — requires @PostConstruct

**See also:** [GE-20260615-d065bf](GE-20260615-d065bf.md) — two @Startup @ApplicationScoped beans have no guaranteed initialization order

ChatModel.doChat(ChatRequest) is the override point for test doubles — not chat(ChatRequest)

## The technique

When implementing a test `ChatModel` without mocks (because `AiMessage`/`ChatResponse` have final methods), override `doChat(ChatRequest)` — not `chat(ChatRequest)`:

```java
ChatModel testModel = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(final ChatRequest request) {
        // inspect request, return appropriate response
        return ChatResponse.builder()
                .aiMessage(new AiMessage("{...json...}"))
                .build();
    }
};
```

`chat(ChatRequest)` is a **default method** in the `ChatModel` interface that calls `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)`, which then calls `doChat(ChatRequest)`. The chain applies listeners, merges request parameters, and fires `onRequest`/`onResponse` hooks. By overriding `doChat()`, the test skips the listener chain and returns directly.

`casehub-engine-api`'s `Agent.execute()` calls `model.chat(request)` which eventually reaches `doChat()`.

## Why this is non-obvious

`chat(ChatRequest)` and `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)` are the visible API methods that developers see in IDE autocompletion. `doChat(ChatRequest)` is buried as an implementation detail — a `default` method with a `throw new RuntimeException("Not implemented")` body that exists specifically as the override target. The JavaDoc doesn't prominently surface this as the intended extension point for test doubles.

**See also:** [GE-20260618-5008f5](../casehub-engine/GE-20260618-5008f5.md) — @Alternative @Priority(10) CDI test bean avoids Quarkus CDI restart (related CDI testing technique)

