CDI fireAsync() inside @Transactional dispatches immediately — observer can run before the triggering transaction commits

## CDI fireAsync() inside @Transactional dispatches immediately — observer can run before the triggering transaction commits

### Symptom

Observer reads entity state immediately after receiving an async event but finds stale or absent data — the entity doesn't exist or still has its pre-update state. No error is thrown; the observer simply acts on wrong data.

### Root cause

`event.fireAsync()` inside a `@Transactional` method dispatches the event immediately on a separate thread, not after the transaction commits. If the observer reads the database, it may not see the uncommitted changes from the dispatching transaction.

### Fix

Fire after the transaction boundary, not inside it:

```java
// Wrong — observer may run before transaction commits
@Transactional
void save(WorkItem item) {
    repo.persist(item);
    event.fireAsync(new WorkItemEvent(item)); // dispatches now, not after commit
}

// Right — fire after commit
void save(WorkItem item) {
    saveTransactional(item);            // commits
    event.fireAsync(new WorkItemEvent(item)); // fires after
}
```

Alternatively, use `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` in a wrapper that commits before returning, then fire from the outer method.

### Why this is non-obvious

CDI developers naturally expect `fireAsync()` to behave like a transactional outbox — dispatching after commit. There is no error, no warning, and the race only manifests when the observer is faster than the commit, which is non-deterministic.

### Alternative — Self-contained event payload (mitigates without restructuring)

If the observer only needs the data that was just written — not data from other tables — design the event record to carry everything the observer needs inline. The observer never reads the database; the race becomes irrelevant.

```java
// Event carries all needed data inline
public record MessageReceivedEvent(
    String channelName, UUID channelId,
    MessageType messageType, String senderId,
    String correlationId, String content) {}

// Observer uses the payload — no DB read needed
void onMessage(@ObservesAsync MessageReceivedEvent event) {
    // event.channelName(), event.correlationId() — already there
    // no messageRepo.findById() needed
}
```

**Pros:** No transaction restructuring; works correctly regardless of dispatch timing; the observer is also simpler and faster.

**Cons:** Only viable when the observer's entire information need is known at dispatch time. Cannot work if the observer needs to join to other tables or react to data not available at the write site.

**See also:** [GE-20260512-6887c9](GE-20260512-6887c9.md) — @ObservesAsync + @Transactional on the same method is unreliable

**See also:** [GE-20260527-cad5ba](GE-20260527-cad5ba.md) — place fireAsync() before internal dispatch to decouple delivery paths in @Transactional methods

**See also:** [GE-20260602-6941d6](GE-20260602-6941d6.md) — separate @ApplicationScoped @Transactional delegate controls commit timing

Synchronous CDI Event.fire() in @Observes StartupEvent propagates observer exceptions — can abort Quarkus startup

## Symptom

Quarkus startup fails with an unexpected exception. The stack trace originates in a CDI observer, propagates through `Event.fire()`, exits the `@Observes StartupEvent` handler, and Quarkus marks startup as failed. The application never becomes ready.

## Context

A startup hook needs to initialise multiple channels and notify external backends via a CDI event:

```java
void onStart(@Observes StartupEvent ev) {
    channelService.listAll().forEach(ch ->
        initChannel(ch.id, new ChannelRef(ch.id, ch.name)));  // initChannel fires CDI event
}
```

If any CDI observer on `ChannelInitialisedEvent` throws, the exception propagates synchronously through `Event.fire()` inside `initChannel()`, through `forEach()`, and out of `onStart()`. Quarkus treats an exception from a StartupEvent handler as a startup failure.

## Root cause

CDI synchronous event dispatch (`Event.fire()`) is call-stack synchronous. The spec requires that exceptions from synchronous observers propagate to the caller of `fire()`. This is correct and intentional CDI behaviour, but it makes `Event.fire()` semantically more like a method call chain than a notification broadcast.

When `fire()` is called from inside a StartupEvent handler, any observer failure flows all the way back to the startup machinery.

## Fix

Wrap each `initChannel()` call (or each `fire()` call) individually so a broken observer doesn't abort the remaining initialisation:

```java
void onStart(@Observes StartupEvent ev) {
    for (Channel ch : channelService.listAll()) {
        try {
            initChannel(ch.id, new ChannelRef(ch.id, ch.name));
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            LOG.errorf(ex, "Failed to initialise gateway for channel %s on startup", ch.id);
        }
    }
}
```

Alternatively, use `Event.fireAsync()` which returns a `CompletionStage` and decouples observer failures from the calling thread entirely — but loses synchronous completion guarantees (backends may not be registered before HTTP requests arrive).

## Why this is non-obvious

`Event.fire()` feels like a broadcast notification — callers typically expect fire-and-forget semantics. The fact that a remote observer's exception propagates synchronously back to the caller is technically specified in the CDI spec but counterintuitive in practice.

The pattern is especially dangerous in startup hooks because developers test with well-behaved observers and only discover the propagation when a new observer is added that can throw.

**See also:** [GE-20260525-f04530](GE-20260525-f04530.md) — inject Event<T> in @QuarkusTest as synchronous test driver | [GE-20260428-f075ef](GE-20260428-f075ef.md) — race-free CompletableFuture pattern for async CDI event tests

**See also:** [GE-20260609-02c68a](GE-20260609-02c68a.md) — CDI StartupEvent @Priority ordering: no-priority fires at 2500, after @Priority(10)

**See also:** [GE-20260501-884024](../quarkus/GE-20260501-884024.md) — @Observes(during = AFTER_SUCCESS) CDI observer silently doesn't fire without JTA transaction

