## What It Is

`StreamingChatModel.chat(ChatRequest, StreamingChatResponseHandler)` is a default method that wraps the caller's handler in an `observingHandler` (for listener infrastructure) before calling `doChat(finalRequest, observingHandler)`. The intended extension point is `doChat()` — not `chat()`.

## Context

When writing test mocks for `StreamingChatModel`, the natural instinct is to implement `chat(ChatRequest, StreamingChatResponseHandler)` directly — it's the method you call in production code. But `chat()` is a `default` method in the interface that routes to `doChat()`. Overriding `chat()` bypasses the listener infrastructure and may produce subtly different behaviour from production.

## How To Use It

```java
StreamingChatModel mock = new StreamingChatModel() {
    @Override
    public void doChat(ChatRequest request, StreamingChatResponseHandler handler) {
        // handler here is the observingHandler — calling it correctly fires both
        // the observer infrastructure and the original caller's callbacks
        handler.onCompleteResponse(
            ChatResponse.builder().aiMessage(AiMessage.from(jsonResponse)).build());
    }
};
```

`doChat()` receives the `observingHandler` wrapper, so calling `handler.onCompleteResponse()` fires listener events AND routes to the caller's original handler. This matches the production call path exactly.

## Why It's Not In The Docs

`doChat()` is the internal override point declared in the interface body. The official documentation only shows `chat()` usage examples. The routing through `observingHandler` is only visible in the source code.

LangChain4j 1.x: ChatLanguageModel renamed to ChatModel; chat() replaced by doChat() as extension point

## What changed

In LangChain4j 1.x, `ChatLanguageModel` was renamed to `ChatModel`. Code that compiled against 0.x fails immediately with `cannot find symbol: class ChatLanguageModel`.

The import path is now `dev.langchain4j.model.chat.ChatModel`.

## Extension point also changed

In 0.x, `ChatLanguageModel` had abstract methods that implementations overrode directly (`generate()`). In 1.x, **all** `ChatModel` methods are `default`. The single extension point is `doChat(ChatRequest)` — override it in anonymous classes or implementations. Lambda stubs fail because `ChatModel` is not a functional interface.

```java
// 0.x — lambda worked (was a functional interface)
ChatLanguageModel stub = messages -> Response.from(AiMessage.from("ok"));

// 1.x — must use anonymous class, override doChat
ChatModel stub = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(ChatRequest request) {
        return ChatResponse.builder().aiMessage(AiMessage.from("ok")).build();
    }
};
```

## Convenience entry points

`ChatModel` retains convenience defaults: `chat(String)` builds a `ChatRequest` from the string and calls `doChat()`. Callers invoking `llm.chat(prompt)` continue to work — only the implementation class and override point changed.

## Why non-obvious

The rename is not surfaced in compiler errors — `ChatLanguageModel` simply doesn't exist in 1.x, so the error looks like a missing dependency rather than a rename. Searching for `ChatLanguageModel` in the new codebase returns nothing. The migration guide exists but isn't the first place developers look when their code stops compiling.

@Alternative on a CDI bean silently suppresses all @DefaultBean beans of the same type — they vanish from the container entirely

### Symptom

`Instance<ChatModel>` iteration returns only the `@Alternative` bean. The `@DefaultBean` ChatModel (registered by quarkus-langchain4j via `SyntheticBeanBuildItem.defaultBean()`) is completely absent from the container — not deprioritized, gone.

### Context

A platform module needed to provide a `ChatModel` adapter (`@Alternative @Priority(10)`) that wraps an `AgentProvider` as a `ChatModel`. The same deployment also has quarkus-langchain4j providing a raw `ChatModel` as `@DefaultBean`. A second bean uses `Instance<ChatModel>` to find the raw model — but after filtering out the adapter, nothing remains.

### What was tried (didn't work)

`@Alternative @Priority(10) @ApplicationScoped` on the adapter bean. Expected: both the adapter and the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel visible in `Instance<ChatModel>`, with `@Priority` disambiguating for direct injection. Actual: the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel vanishes entirely.

### Root cause

ArC's `@DefaultBean` semantics state: *"the bean will only be used if no other bean of this type is configured."* An `@Alternative` with `@Priority` counts as "another bean" — it suppresses the `@DefaultBean` entirely, removing it from the container. This is not priority ordering — it is total suppression.

### Fix

Use `@DefaultBean @Priority(10)` instead of `@Alternative @Priority(10)`.

```java
// WRONG — suppresses quarkus-langchain4j's @DefaultBean ChatModel
@Alternative
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }

// RIGHT — coexists with other @DefaultBean ChatModel beans
@DefaultBean
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }
```

Two `@DefaultBean` beans coexist — neither suppresses the other. `@Priority(10)` wins for direct `@Inject ChatModel` injection. `Instance<ChatModel>` sees both, enabling runtime filtering.

A consumer-provided non-`@DefaultBean` ChatModel properly overrides both defaults — the `@DefaultBean` suppression rule works as expected when a "real" bean is present.

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers expect `@Alternative` to win the injection point but leave other beans in the container for `Instance` lookup. The mental model is "priority ordering among all candidates" when the reality is "total removal of @DefaultBean beans when any non-default bean exists."

The ArC javadoc confirms: *"Default beans can optionally declare @Priority. Priority value is used for bean ordering and during typesafe resolution to disambiguate multiple matching default beans."* This `@DefaultBean @Priority` pattern is the correct way to have two platform-provided defaults with deterministic selection.

### Why this fix

`@DefaultBean @Priority` is architecturally correct — both beans are "defaults" that yield to consumer-provided beans. `@Alternative` implies the bean is an override, which is semantically wrong when both beans are platform infrastructure that should coexist.

### Alternatives considered

- **CDI qualifiers** (`@Named`, custom qualifier) — would work but forces callers to qualify injection points. Breaks the "just add to classpath" activation model.
- **Conditional activation** (`@IfBuildProperty`) — too rigid; the coexistence scenario is legitimate in deployments using both adapters.

**See also:** GE-20260601-fcf0d9 — two @DefaultBean beans for the same type give AmbiguousResolutionException, not Unsatisfied | GE-20260623-c651a1 — removing @Alternative from one bean in a multi-implementation chain silently changes resolution

Default interface method as bridge consolidator — combine two-step activation checks across many implementors

## The Problem

A Phase 1 migration bridge requires each of N plugin classes to evaluate a two-step activation check in `canActivate(CaseFile)`: first check `requires()` key presence, then check `activateIf()` extra gates. Writing this inline in 8 plugins creates brittle duplication — if the combination logic changes, all 8 must be updated.

## The Technique

Add a `default` method to the interface that combines the two steps. Each plugin bridge delegates to it in a single expression:

**In the interface:**
```java
public interface TaskDefinition {
    default Set<String> requires() { return Set.of(); }
    default Predicate<CaseContext> activateIf() { return ctx -> true; }

/** Phase 1 bridge helper — mirrors Phase 2 SequenceWorker evaluation order. */
    default boolean testActivation(CaseContext ctx) {
        return requires().stream().allMatch(ctx::contains) && activateIf().test(ctx);
    }
}
```

**In each of the 8 plugin bridges:**
```java
@Override
public boolean canActivate(CaseFile caseFile) {
    return testActivation(new CaseFileContext(caseFile));
}
```

## Why Non-Obvious

The instinct is to extract a static utility method or write it inline. The `default` method approach is better here because:
1. It lives on the interface that all implementations share — no import needed
2. It encodes the Phase 2 semantics explicitly (requires first, then activateIf) in the contract, not in utility code
3. When Phase 2 arrives and bridge methods are deleted, the `default` method serves as documentation of the intended evaluation order

The technique also prevents the subtle bug where refactoring `activateIf()` to remove key re-checks (making it "extra gates only") breaks the bridge — the `testActivation()` helper re-adds the key check from `requires()`, so the bridge stays correct.

CDI container wiring vs service-loader wiring in large JVM frameworks

## Pattern

Large JVM frameworks that expose extension points make a foundational choice: wire extensions via **CDI container injection** or via **service-loader / explicit registration**. Both achieve the same structural depth (thousands of interfaces, deep abstraction hierarchies) but differ radically in how dependencies flow at runtime.

### CDI container wiring (Quarkus style)

Extensions are beans. Callers inject them via `@Inject`, `Instance<T>`, or `@Any Instance<T>`. The CDI container owns lifetime and resolution.

```java
// Extension point
public interface ExpiryPolicy {
    String name();
    boolean isExpired(Session s, Duration timeout);
}

// Discovery — zero explicit registration
@ApplicationScoped
public class PolicyRegistry {
    @Inject @Any Instance<ExpiryPolicy> policies;

public ExpiryPolicy get(String name) {
        return policies.stream()
            .filter(p -> p.name().equals(name))
            .findFirst().orElseThrow();
    }
}
```

### Service-loader wiring (Hibernate style)

Extensions are registered via `META-INF/services/<InterfaceFQN>` files or explicit `ServiceRegistry` calls. The framework owns resolution; no CDI container required.

```java
// META-INF/services/org.hibernate.integrator.spi.Integrator
// → com.example.MyIntegrator

// Discovery — explicit service lookup
ServiceLoader<Integrator> loader =
    ServiceLoader.load(Integrator.class, classLoader);
```

## Why this is non-obvious

The two approaches look structurally identical at a coarse level — same number of interfaces, same abstraction depth ratio. A structural fingerprint alone won't distinguish them. The signal is in the **injection-to-file ratio**: CDI-wired frameworks approach 0.4 injections/file; service-loader frameworks stay near 0.002. That gap (200×) survives normalisation and is the discriminator.

This matters when **integrating the two styles**: a Hibernate extension brought into a Quarkus application must be wrapped in a CDI producer or adapter bean — the wiring strategies don't compose directly.

### Alternatives considered

- **Manual factory / registry**: explicit `Map<String, Extension>` maintained in code. Works, but requires every extension author to register manually. Fragile at scale.
- **Reflection-based scanning**: scan classpath for implementations. Non-deterministic ordering, classloading hazards, slow startup.
- **Both at once (hybrid)**: use service-loader for bootstrap discovery, CDI for runtime injection. Adds complexity; only warranted when a framework must work both inside and outside a CDI container.

