@RequestScoped CDI bean silently fails in Quarkus @ConsumeEvent handlers — no error, no WorkItem

### Symptom
Integration test expects a WorkItem to be created after firing a case event. The assertion sees an empty store — `Expected size: 1 but was: 0`. No error, no exception, no log warning.

### Context
A `@ConsumeEvent(blocking = true)` handler calls `WorkItemService.create()`, which transitively injects `TenantScopedPrincipal` — a `@RequestScoped` bean. The handler runs on a Quarkus worker thread where no request context is active. CDI proxy throws `ContextNotActiveException` internally, but the event bus swallows it — the handler appears to complete normally.

The `@RequestScoped` bean wins CDI resolution over a `@DefaultBean @ApplicationScoped` alternative because non-default beans have higher priority. So the broken bean is always selected.

### What was tried (didn't work)
- Checking event bus wiring (correct — other handlers on the same bus work)
- Verifying WorkItemStore contents (empty — the create call never completes)
- Adding `@ActivateRequestContext` to the test method (doesn't help — handler runs on a different thread)

### Root cause
`@ConsumeEvent` handlers — even with `blocking = true` — do not activate a CDI request context. Any `@RequestScoped` bean in the injection chain throws `ContextNotActiveException`. The Vert.x event bus catches the exception and does not propagate it to the caller (fire-and-forget semantics).

### Fix
Exclude the `@RequestScoped` bean from the test CDI context and provide an `@ApplicationScoped` replacement:

```properties
# application.properties
quarkus.arc.exclude-types=io.casehub.work.runtime.service.TenantScopedPrincipal
```

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class NoOpCurrentPrincipal implements CurrentPrincipal {
    @Override public String actorId() { return "system"; }
    @Override public Set<String> groups() { return Set.of(); }
    @Override public String tenancyId() { return TenancyConstants.DEFAULT_TENANT_ID; }
    @Override public boolean isCrossTenantAdmin() { return false; }
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious
The failure is completely silent. No exception in logs, no test error beyond the assertion. The `@RequestScoped` bean wins CDI resolution automatically (higher priority than `@DefaultBean`), so you never suspect it's the problem. You debug the event bus, the handler logic, and the store — all correct. The request scope issue only surfaces when you trace the full injection chain.

Static test capture list in @ObservesAsync @Mock bean is a data race with the test thread

### Symptom

Flaky test results when using `Awaitility` to wait for an `@ObservesAsync` CDI event to be
processed. Occasionally the capture list appears empty despite the observer having run, or
entries from a previous test contaminate the current one.

Under Quarkus's default serial test execution the window is narrow and failures are rare.
Under parallel test execution or higher thread-pool concurrency the race is consistent.

### Context

The common pattern for testing `@ObservesAsync` CDI events in `@QuarkusTest` is a `@Mock`
connector or observer bean with a static `List` field that captures processed items:

```java
@Mock
public class TestSlackConnector implements Connector {
    public static final List<ConnectorMessage> sent = new ArrayList<>();  // ← data race
    public static boolean shouldThrow = false;                            // ← visibility hazard

@Override
    public void send(ConnectorMessage message) {
        if (shouldThrow) throw new RuntimeException("failure");
        sent.add(message);
    }
}
```

The test thread reads `sent.isEmpty()` inside an `Awaitility.await()` loop. The `@ObservesAsync`
observer runs on a background `ManagedExecutorService` thread and calls `send()`, which writes
to `sent`. There is no memory barrier between the threads — both the list write and the boolean
read are unsynchronised.

### Root cause

`@ObservesAsync` dispatches to a container-managed thread pool, not the test thread. A plain
`ArrayList` is not thread-safe: concurrent reads and writes can produce `ConcurrentModificationException`,
stale visibility (the test thread sees an empty list after the observer has added an element),
or torn reads. A plain `boolean` field has no visibility guarantee — the test thread may read
a stale `false` even after the executor thread wrote `true`.

### Fix

Use thread-safe types for all static capture fields in `@Mock` beans observed by async events:

```java
@Mock
public class TestSlackConnector implements Connector {
    public static final List<ConnectorMessage> sent = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>();  // ✅ thread-safe
    public static volatile boolean shouldThrow = false;                              // ✅ visible across threads

@Override
    public void send(ConnectorMessage message) {
        if (shouldThrow) throw new RuntimeException("failure");
        sent.add(message);
    }
}
```

Clear in `@BeforeEach`:
```java
@BeforeEach
void setUp() {
    TestSlackConnector.sent.clear();
    TestSlackConnector.shouldThrow = false;
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers are aware of thread safety in production code but rarely apply it to test capture
fields, especially when the observer pattern is hidden behind CDI events. The `@Mock` annotation
suggests the bean is a test fixture — it is easy to overlook that CDI still dispatches it on a
real background thread. Under Quarkus's default serial test model failures are rare enough
that many codebases ship with this race latent indefinitely.

**See also:** [GE-20260517-712fe5](GE-20260517-712fe5.md) — @ApplicationScoped capture bean with CountDownLatch — the correct technique | [GE-20260522-bc642c](GE-20260522-bc642c.md) — ArrayList unsafe for @ObservesAsync test captures

**See also:** [GE-20260618-303fa2](GE-20260618-303fa2.md) — QuarkusTest CaseEngine worker thread updates CDI singletons after gameTick() returns

MutableCurrentPrincipal @ApplicationScoped state leaks between @QuarkusTest classes — silent empty results

### Symptom
Tests pass in isolation, fail in suite — tenant-scoped store queries return empty `Optional` or empty `List`, not errors. No CDI exception, no `NullPointerException`. The failure is completely silent.

### Context
A `MutableCurrentPrincipal` test bean (`@ApplicationScoped @Alternative @Priority(100)`) provides mutable `tenancyId` for tenancy isolation tests. Tenancy tests call `setTenancyId(TENANT_B)` and reset via `@BeforeEach` within their own class. But `@ApplicationScoped` beans survive across `@QuarkusTest` classes — after the last test method of a tenancy test class, the bean retains `TENANT_B`. Subsequent test classes expecting `DEFAULT_TENANT_ID` silently get wrong query results.

### What was tried (didn't work)
- Adding `@AfterEach` to tenancy test classes — fragile, easy to miss for new tests
- Making each non-tenancy test inject and reset the principal — doesn't scale

### Root cause
`@ApplicationScoped` CDI beans persist across `@QuarkusTest` classes within the same Quarkus test application lifecycle. JUnit test class ordering is non-deterministic. A tenancy test class that sets `tenancyId = TENANT_B` in its last test method leaves the bean in that state for all subsequent classes.

### Fix
Register a `QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback` via ServiceLoader that resets the principal before every test method across all test classes:

```java
public class MutablePrincipalResetCallback implements QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback {
    @Override
    public void beforeEach(QuarkusTestMethodContext context) {
        var container = Arc.container();
        if (container != null) {
            var handle = container.instance(MutableCurrentPrincipal.class);
            if (handle.isAvailable()) {
                handle.get().reset();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Register in `META-INF/services/io.quarkus.test.junit.callback.QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback`.

### Why this is non-obvious
The failure is silent — tenant-scoped queries filter by `tenancyId` and return empty results when the ID doesn't match. No exception is thrown. The symptoms (empty Optional, empty List) look like missing test data, not wrong tenant context. You only discover the real cause when test ordering changes or a new tenancy test class is added.

### Why this fix
A ServiceLoader callback is infrastructure-level — it fires before every test method in every `@QuarkusTest` class without requiring any per-class wiring. Individual `@BeforeEach` resets are fragile (miss one class, silently break another). The callback makes the problem structurally impossible.

### Alternatives considered
- Per-class `@BeforeEach` reset: fragile, doesn't scale
- `@RequestScoped` principal: would need request context activation in every test, breaks `@ApplicationScoped` store injection patterns
- JUnit `@Order` on test classes: masks the problem, doesn't fix it

**See also:** [GE-20260512-e552f7](GE-20260512-e552f7.md) — @ApplicationScoped bean state persists across @QuarkusTest classes | [GE-20260612-279b44](GE-20260612-279b44.md) — CDI bean ordering non-determinism causes registry key collision | [GE-20260519-12efe9](GE-20260519-12efe9.md) — QuarkusTestProfile.getEnabledAlternatives() scopes @Alternative to single test class

Poll a semantically-meaningful ready signal, not just HTTP 200, for fast-starting services

## What it is

When wrapping a backend service in an Electron app, poll a domain-specific ready signal rather than just checking for HTTP 200 on the health endpoint. The service may respond to HTTP before it has finished initialising its application state.

## Context

A Quarkus replay service starts in ~1.7s (JVM boot) but takes an additional ~2s to parse replay files and load 22,000+ GAME_EVENTS into memory. Polling `/q/health` (HTTP 200) fires at 1.7s — the Electron window loads the visualiser before the game loop has run its first tick, producing a black screen because the WebSocket delivers no data yet.

## The technique

Poll a business-level endpoint that only returns a valid response once the application is genuinely ready for user interaction:

```javascript
function isReplayReady(cb) {
  const req = http.get('http://localhost:8080/qa/replay/status', res => {
    if (res.statusCode !== 200) { cb(false); return; }
    let body = '';
    res.on('data', d => body += d);
    res.on('end', () => {
      try { cb(JSON.parse(body).totalLoops > 0); }
      catch { cb(false); }
    });
  });
  req.on('error', () => cb(false));
  req.setTimeout(1000, () => { req.destroy(); cb(false); });
}
```

`totalLoops > 0` means the replay file is fully parsed and at least one scheduler tick has completed — the WebSocket will immediately deliver a valid game frame.

## Why this is non-obvious

Health endpoints (`/q/health`, `/actuator/health`) are designed to signal that the process is alive, not that application-level initialisation is complete. The two can be seconds apart. Most examples show polling health — the gap is only visible when the app loads UI before the data is ready.

ChannelGateway.fanOut() fires backend.post() on a virtual thread INSIDE @Transactional — SSE/push events precede DB commit

## ChannelGateway.fanOut() Fires backend.post() Before the DB Transaction Commits

### Symptom

A client receives an SSE event (or any push notification) indicating a task is "completed",
polls `GET /resource/{id}` immediately, and gets the previous (non-terminal) state — as if
the event was premature. The actual DB state catches up within milliseconds, but the window
is real and reproducible under load.

### Context

```java
@Transactional
public DispatchResult dispatch(MessageDispatch d) {
    // ... enforcement, persistence ...
    messageStore.put(message);        // persisted inside the transaction
    channelGateway.fanOut(ch.id, ...); // fires post() on a virtual thread
    return result;
}  // transaction commits here, AFTER fanOut() returns
```

`ChannelGateway.fanOut()` implementation:

```java
public void fanOut(UUID channelId, String channelName, OutboundMessage message) {
    for (BackendEntry entry : registry) {
        Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {  // ← starts NOW, inside the transaction
            backend.post(ref, message);   // SSE push happens here, pre-commit
        });
    }
}
```

The virtual thread is started immediately when `fanOut()` is called. The JTA transaction
has NOT committed yet — `messageStore.put()` has been called but the DB write is pending.
The virtual thread executes `backend.post()` (which sends SSE events, calls webhooks, etc.)
before the parent thread's `@Transactional` proxy commits.

### Root cause

Java virtual threads are not structured concurrency participants. `Thread.ofVirtual().start()`
starts the thread immediately regardless of any enclosing JTA transaction. The JTA spec has
no mechanism to delay thread start until after commit.

This affects all backends, not just SSE — Kafka producers, HTTP callbacks, and any other
notification dispatched via `Thread.ofVirtual()` inside a `@Transactional` method share
this race.

### Fix (application-side mitigation)

**Option 1 — Client-side retry:** Document the behavior and advise clients to treat push
events as triggers, not guarantees. The client retries the poll with a short backoff after
receiving an event:

```java
// Client: on SSE event received, poll with retry
retryWithBackoff(3, 50ms, () -> pollUntilTerminal(taskId));
```

**Option 2 — Post-commit dispatch:** Use JTA `TransactionSynchronizationRegistry` to delay
`fanOut()` until after commit (already used in `MessageObserverDispatcher`):

```java
tsr.registerInterposedSynchronization(new Synchronization() {
    public void afterCompletion(int status) {
        if (status == Status.STATUS_COMMITTED) {
            channelGateway.fanOut(ch.id, channelName, outbound);
        }
    }
    public void beforeCompletion() {}
});
```

This is the correct fix for any backend where post-commit ordering is required.

### Why this is non-obvious

The natural reading of `Thread.ofVirtual().start(...)` inside a service method is "this
runs concurrently with the rest of the method." Developers rarely think about whether the
JTA transaction has committed when the thread body executes. Virtual threads are further
confusing because they park on blocking I/O and appear to run inline — making it even less
obvious they escape the JTA context. The `@Transactional` annotation on the service method
gives a false sense that the entire method body (including any work it spawns) is
transactionally isolated.

**See also:** [GE-20260605-494ed0](GE-20260605-494ed0.md) — ChannelGateway.fanOut() delivers to backends on virtual threads — @QuarkusTest assertions fail before backend fires

Stateless multi-tier SLA escalation via candidateGroups — no state storage or decision serialization needed

## Technique

When a `SlaBreachPolicy` implementation needs multi-tier escalation (first breach → escalate to group A; if group A's task also expires → fail terminally), the policy does NOT need to serialise the decision chain or store tier state externally. The WorkItem's own `candidateGroups` field carries the tier information.

`ExpiryLifecycleService` calls `onBreach()` again when the escalated WorkItem expires. At that point, `SlaBreachContext.task().candidateGroups()` contains the groups set during the first escalation. The policy reads this to determine the tier:

```java
public BreachDecision onBreach(SlaBreachContext ctx) {
    Preferences p = ctx.preferences();
    String escalationGroup = p.getOrDefault(ESCALATION_GROUP).value();

// Second breach — escalated WorkItem also expired
    if (ctx.task().candidateGroups().contains(escalationGroup)) {
        return new BreachDecision.Fail(
            p.getOrDefault(BREACH_TERMINAL_REASON).value());
    }

// First breach — escalate to senior group
    return EscalateTo.to(escalationGroup)
        .withDeadline(Duration.ofHours(p.getOrDefault(ESCALATION_HOURS).value()));
}
```

The same `onBreach()` method handles both tiers. No state is stored between calls; no `Chained` wrapper is needed for the normal two-tier case.

## Why this is non-obvious

The intuitive approach is to serialize the decision tree into the WorkItem (payload, label, or case context key), then deserialize it on the next breach to know what to execute. This requires a `Chained` wrapper or complex state management. The elegant solution is to recognize that `candidateGroups` already encodes the tier: if the escalation group is already assigned, the item has been through one breach cycle.

## When to use

- Two-tier SLA escalation (first breach → escalate to group B; second breach → terminal action)
- Any policy where the WorkItem's current assignment state encodes which tier has been reached
- Preference-driven policies where tier thresholds come from `PreferenceProvider`

## Critical caveat — candidateGroups is REPLACED after escalation

`ExpiryLifecycleService.executeEscalateTo()` does `item.candidateGroups = String.join(",", escalate.groups())` — it **replaces** the entire field with only the escalation group. The original groups are gone after the first breach.

Consequence: if the policy's first-tier check tests for the **original** group only, it will return `Fail` on the second breach instead of reaching the `Exhausted` branch — silently making `Exhausted` unreachable. The guard must cover both groups:

```java
// WRONG — "regulatory-affairs" gone after first escalation
boolean isRegulatory = ctx.task().candidateGroups().contains("regulatory-affairs");

// CORRECT — test both tiers
boolean isRegulatory = ctx.task().candidateGroups().contains("regulatory-affairs")
                    || ctx.task().candidateGroups().contains("regulatory-leadership");
if (!isRegulatory) return new Fail("no-policy");
if (ctx.task().candidateGroups().contains("regulatory-leadership")) return new Exhausted("...");
return EscalateTo.to("regulatory-leadership").withDeadline(Duration.ofHours(48));
```

Verified in `ExpiryLifecycleService.executeEscalateTo()` source: `item.candidateGroups = String.join(",", escalate.groups())` — line runs before `workItemStore.put(item)`.

## When not to use

- Three or more tiers with overlapping group assignments (candidateGroups may be ambiguous)
- Non-group-based tiers (e.g. tier determined by breach count — use a case context signal instead)

Lock-outside-transaction pattern for safe concurrent sequence assignment in CDI/JTA

### The technique

To safely assign sequence numbers across concurrent `@ObservesAsync` event handlers without a database-level sequence, acquire an application-level lock **outside** the transaction boundary. The lock must be held until after the transaction commits — not just until the persistence call returns.

The critical requirement: the `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` must be on a **separate CDI bean** (not `this`), so the CDI proxy applies the transaction interceptor. Self-invocation bypasses the proxy and the transaction never starts.

```java
// Non-transactional observer — holds the lock
@ApplicationScoped
public class AmlTrustRoutingObserver {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<UUID, Object> subjectLocks = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

@Inject AmlTrustAttestationRepository attestationRepo; // @Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)

public void onWorkerDecision(@ObservesAsync WorkerDecisionEvent event) {
        final UUID attestationSubject = attestationSubjectFor(event.caseId());
        final AmlTrustRoutingAttestation entry = buildEntry(event, attestationSubject);

// Lock acquired BEFORE transaction starts — held until AFTER it commits
        final Object lock = subjectLocks.computeIfAbsent(attestationSubject, k -> new Object());
        synchronized (lock) {
            attestationRepo.saveWithSequence(entry); // REQUIRES_NEW via CDI proxy
        } // lock released AFTER REQUIRES_NEW committed
    }
}

// Separate bean — @Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW) applied by CDI proxy
@ApplicationScoped
public class AmlTrustAttestationRepository {
    @Transactional(TxType.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public AmlTrustRoutingAttestation saveWithSequence(AmlTrustRoutingAttestation entry) {
        Integer max = em.createQuery(
            "SELECT MAX(e.sequenceNumber) FROM LedgerEntry e WHERE e.subjectId = :sid",
            Integer.class).setParameter("sid", entry.subjectId).getSingleResult();
        entry.sequenceNumber = max == null ? 1 : max + 1;
        em.persist(entry);
        return entry;
    }
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

The obvious approach is `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` on the observer itself with `synchronized` inside. This fails: the `synchronized` block exits **before** the REQUIRES_NEW commits (the transaction commits when the method returns, which is after `synchronized` exits). The next thread then reads the same `max` before the first write is committed.

Putting the lock inside `saveWithSequence` (self-invocation) also fails: `this.saveWithSequence()` bypasses the CDI proxy, so no transaction starts at all.

The correct structure: lock in the non-transactional outer method, call the `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` method through a CDI-injected reference. Transaction starts when the injected method is entered, commits when it returns, all while the lock is still held.

### Constraints

- Requires single-JVM deployment (application-level lock doesn't span JVMs)
- Lock map grows with unique subjects — add eviction if subjects are unbounded in production
- Only needed when a database-level sequence or `SELECT FOR UPDATE` pattern is unavailable
- CDI proxy requirement means the `@Transactional` method must be on a public method of a `@ApplicationScoped` or `@RequestScoped` bean, not a `@Singleton` (proxy injection still required)

### Why this fix

Database sequences (CREATE SEQUENCE) would be cleaner for true scalability but require a Flyway migration and a per-subject table entry. This pattern solves the problem with zero schema changes, is easily testable, and makes the concurrency model explicit in code.

**See also:** [GE-20260609-62a1a7](GE-20260609-62a1a7.md) — H2 MERGE WHEN NOT MATCHED races under concurrent transactions (the gotcha this technique solves)

Read-modify-write on thread-safe store is not atomic — concurrent writers lose updates

### Symptom

Under concurrent writes, a list value in a thread-safe store ends up with fewer entries than expected — some updates are silently lost. The store itself is thread-safe but the caller's update is not.

### Context

Any pattern where a caller (a) reads a mutable value from a thread-safe store, (b) modifies it outside the store, then (c) writes it back. Common with lists that are stored as values in a `ConcurrentHashMap` or similar.

### What was tried (didn't work)

```java
// RACE: two threads both read the same list, modify it, write back — last write wins
public static void recordWorkerCompletion(CaseContextImpl ctx, String workerName) {
    WritablePanelImpl episodic = ctx.writablePanel(ContextPanel.EPISODIC);
    List<Map<String, Object>> workers = episodic.getList("workers", Map.class); // read (lock released)
    // ← another thread reads the same list here ←
    workers = new ArrayList<>(workers);
    // ... modify workers list ...
    episodic.set("workers", workers); // write (lock acquired) — may overwrite concurrent write
}
```

`getList()` acquires and releases the read lock. The modification runs unguarded. `set()` acquires the write lock. Between the read and write, another thread calling the same method reads the same stale list and its write overwrites the first thread's increment.

### Root cause

Thread-safety of individual operations on a store does not make sequences of those operations atomic. The entire read-modify-write sequence must execute under a single lock.

### Fix

Hold the write lock for the full read-modify-write sequence using an atomic update method:

```java
// Add to the store class:
public void engineUpdate(String key, UnaryOperator<Object> updater) {
    lock.writeLock().lock();
    try {
        Object current = data.get(key);
        Object updated = updater.apply(current);
        if (updated != null) data.put(key, updated);
        else data.remove(key);
    } finally {
        lock.writeLock().unlock();
    }
}

// Caller uses the atomic update:
episodic.engineUpdate("workers", currentValue -> {
    List<Map<String, Object>> workers = currentValue instanceof List
        ? new ArrayList<>((List<Map<String, Object>>) currentValue)
        : new ArrayList<>();
    // ... modify workers ...
    return workers;
});
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers typically understand that individual operations on `ConcurrentHashMap` are thread-safe and assume this extends to "I read it safely, I write it safely, so the sequence is safe." The race window is invisible in unit tests because tests run sequentially by default. The bug only appears under load — Quartz worker completion callbacks, for example, can arrive concurrently for the same case and trigger simultaneous list updates.

