emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()) — correct way to shift blocking I/O off Vert.x IO thread in a reactive SPI

## Context

A reactive SPI method returns `Uni<T>` and needs to make a blocking call (e.g. HTTP to an embedding service, JDBC, file I/O). The SPI is called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler (Vert.x event bus) which runs on the Vert.x IO thread unless `blocking = true` is set.

## Technique

Use `.emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())` on the `Uni` **before** the blocking operation. This shifts the execution to the Mutiny default worker pool:

```java
@Override
public Uni<AgentAssignment> select(AgentRoutingContext context, List<AgentCandidate> candidates) {
    // Classify (in-memory, fast — can stay on caller thread)
    List<ClassifiedCandidate> classified = classifier.classify(candidates, ...);

return Uni.createFrom()
        .voidItem()
        .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())  // shift here, before blocking work
        .map(ignored -> {
            // Everything from here runs on the worker pool
            float[] queryVector = embeddingProvider.embed(queryText);  // blocking HTTP call
            // ... build scored candidates ...
            return TrustCandidateClassifier.decide(classified, scored, capability);
        });
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

Three common but wrong alternatives:

**1. `Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blockingOperation())`**
Executes the supplier on the thread that subscribes (the IO thread). Still blocks if called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler.

**2. `@Blocking` on the handler method**
Moves the *entire* handler to a worker thread, including all in-memory work before the SPI call. Wasteful and scatters the threading decision into the caller rather than the SPI implementation.

**3. `Uni.createFrom().emitter(em -> { em.complete(blocking()); })`**
Also executes on the subscribing thread unless `.emitOn()` is chained.

The correct model: the `Uni` pipeline is lazy. `.emitOn(workerPool)` inserts a thread-handoff at that point in the pipeline — everything downstream of it executes on the worker pool when the `Uni` is subscribed. Place it immediately before the first blocking call, after any fast in-memory preparation.

## Constraints

Requires `io.smallrye.mutiny:mutiny` and `io.smallrye.mutiny.infrastructure.Infrastructure` on the classpath (shipped with Quarkus). `Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()` is the standard Mutiny executor for blocking work — do not pass a custom executor unless you need isolation.

**See also:** [GE-20260529-b994c2](GE-20260529-b994c2.md) — Uni.createFrom().item(supplier) with emitOn(): supplier still runs on subscription thread (use runSubscriptionOn instead)

Two @Startup @ApplicationScoped Quarkus beans have no guaranteed initialization order — @PostConstruct side effects are unreliable across beans

### Symptom

Bean A's `@PostConstruct` sets a shared global (e.g. `Path.setDefaultParser()`). Bean B's `@PostConstruct` calls code that depends on that global. Works in some environments, fails silently or intermittently in others because the order in which Quarkus initialises `@Startup` beans is not defined.

### Context

Any Quarkus application with two or more `@Startup @ApplicationScoped` beans where one bean's `@PostConstruct` produces a side effect (global state, static field, registry population) that another bean's `@PostConstruct` consumes.

### Root cause

CDI specifies no initialization ordering between two `@Startup @ApplicationScoped` beans. The order is implementation-defined and can vary between test and production environments. `@Startup` only guarantees that all such beans initialise before the first non-startup request — not relative to each other.

### Fix

Each `@Startup` bean reads `@ConfigProperty` directly rather than depending on another bean's `@PostConstruct` side effect. Pass the config value explicitly to helpers that need it.

```java
// BAD — depends on PathParserConfigurator.@PostConstruct having set the default parser
Path parser = Path.getDefaultParser(); // may be null or default at this point

// GOOD — read the same config key directly; CDI injects @ConfigProperty fields
// before @PostConstruct, regardless of @Startup ordering between beans
@ConfigProperty(name = "casehub.platform.path.separator", defaultValue = "/")
String pathSeparator;

@PostConstruct
void load() {
    PathParser parser = PathParser.of(pathSeparator); // explicit, no cross-bean dependency
    // ...
}
```

`@ConfigProperty` fields are always injected before `@PostConstruct` runs — that guarantee is per-bean, not cross-bean, and is reliable.

### Why this is non-obvious

`@Startup` implies "at startup" — developers assume multiple `@Startup` beans initialise in a predictable order (e.g. dependency graph or declaration order). The CDI spec guarantee is only that they initialise before the first non-startup request, not relative to each other. The failure is intermittent and environment-dependent, making it hard to reproduce reliably.

